Lab materials

Data: transaction-level data set about campagin donations to United States congressional candidates, 2009–2018, by ‘single issue’ groups specifically abortion lobby.

Census data from US Census Bureau, to learn about women’s wealth in candidates’ respective congressional districts.

Question #1: does pro-choice lobby invest more resources in districts where women are wealthier or where women are poorer? Think what women’s wealth might overlap with: empowerment? numbers in labour force? values? family?

Question #2: does receipt of pro-choice contributions predict election outcome? Are Democratic candidates receiving high pro-choice contributions more likely to win (lose)? Think what high contributions might overlap with: running on feminist agenda? candidate gender?

ftm <- read.csv("ftm.csv")

Correlation test.

choice <- ftm2[ftm2$Specific_Business=="Abortion policy, pro-choice",]
life <- ftm2[ftm2$Specific_Business=="Abortion policy, pro-life",]

plot(choice$total,choice$med_f)

cor.test(choice$total, choice$med_f)
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  choice$total and choice$med_f
## t = -0.73915, df = 377, p-value = 0.4603
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.13824529  0.06293532
## sample estimates:
##         cor 
## -0.03804045
choice2 <- choice[choice$total < 50000 & choice$General_Party=="Democratic",] # removing outliers
plot(choice2$total,choice2$med_f, ylab="income", xlab="$ pro-choice contributions")

cor.test(choice2$total, choice2$med_f)
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  choice2$total and choice2$med_f
## t = -1.8977, df = 341, p-value = 0.05858
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.205893082  0.003709121
## sample estimates:
##        cor 
## -0.1022265

T-test.

Does the amount of pro-choice donation (Democratic candidates only) predict winning a seat?

table(choice2$Status_of_Candidate)
## 
##                Default Winner           Lost        Pending            Won 
##              0              1            150              6            186
mean(choice2$total[choice2$Status_of_Candidate=="Won"]) # average pro-choice contributions to winning Democratic candidates
## [1] 5774.699
mean(choice2$total[choice2$Status_of_Candidate=="Lost"]) # average pro-choice contributions to losing Democratic candidates
## [1] 7467.381
choice2$win <- NA
choice2$win[choice2$Status_of_Candidate=="Won"] <- 1
choice2$win[choice2$Status_of_Candidate=="Lost"] <- 0
boxplot(total~win, data=choice2, medlty=0, ylab="$ total", xlab="Winner?")
means <- tapply(choice2$total,choice2$win,mean)
points(means,col="red",pch=18)

t.test(total ~ win, data=choice2)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  total by win
## t = 2.5943, df = 286.83, p-value = 0.009965
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##   408.4634 2976.9007
## sample estimates:
## mean in group 0 mean in group 1 
##        7467.381        5774.699

Chi square test.

Looking at high versus low donations, dichotomised this time, which is predictive of winning/losing?

hist(choice2$total, main="$ total")
abline(v=median(choice2$total),col="red",lwd=3) # the median
abline(v=mean(choice2$total),col="blue",lwd=2, lty=2) # the median
legend(10000,200,legend=c("Median","Mean"), col = c("red","blue"),lty=1:2,bty = "n")

choice2$total2 <- ifelse(choice2$total <= median(choice2$total), 0, 1)

table(choice2$win,choice2$total2) # rows are winning status, cols are low versus high donations
##    
##       0   1
##   0  78  72
##   1 121  65
round(prop.table(table(choice2$win,choice2$total2)),2)
##    
##        0    1
##   0 0.23 0.21
##   1 0.36 0.19
chisq.test(choice2$win,choice2$total2)
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test with Yates' continuity correction
## 
## data:  choice2$win and choice2$total2
## X-squared = 5.3312, df = 1, p-value = 0.02095
